The paper discusses the use of reservoir computing, a type of recurrent neural network, for processing electrocardiogram signals to classify heartbeat anomalies. This falls under the category of neural networks and machine learning, making cs.NE the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of this technology in wearable devices, which could fall under the sub-categories of human-computer interaction (cs.HC) and embedded systems (cs.EM). Additionally, the paper uses data from the MIT-BIH arrhythmia database, which is related to biomedical engineering (cs.BIO). Finally, the paper discusses the problem of imbalanced classes, which is a common issue in machine learning and could fall under the sub-category of learning theory (cs.LG).
